This is the solution I am using. It still uses a global function as the handler, but it is the best way I've found to get the notification inside of your controller. The following code is following iOS push registration (the config object has "ecb" set to "onNotificationAPN")

inside a `<script>` element in index.html:

``` javascript
var onNotificationAPN = function(notification) {
  var elem = angular.element(document.querySelector('[ng-app]'));
  var rootScope = elem.injector().get('$rootScope');
  rootScope.$broadcast('pushNotificationReceived', notification);
};
```

in your your controller:

``` javascript
$scope.$on('pushNotificationReceived', function(event, notification) {
  // handle notification here
});
```

Hope this helps. I'm exploring ways of embedded some of this logic inside ngCordova in my spare time. If I find a way I may put a pull request up and see if the authors like it.

