aka-Ani:
I'm not too knowledgeable on how to contribute to the ngCordova project with your custom implementation of a plugin, but making an angular wrapper for a plugin is not too difficult. Basically, take a look at the ng-cordova plugins folder:
https://github.com/driftyco/ng-cordova/tree/master/src/plugins

You can see there is a js file for each wrapper. Let us take the ble.js file for example:
https://github.com/driftyco/ng-cordova/blob/master/src/plugins/ble.js

You can see all you need to do is define a module and factory which implements each of the functions that the plugin provides:

``` javascript
angular.module('ngCordova.plugins.ble', [])

  .factory('$cordovaBLE', ['$q', function ($q) {
```

You would have to make your own names and stuff.
Here is the github page for the plugin:
https://github.com/don/cordova-plugin-ble-central

So let's take the scan function. If you were using the plugin directly, the structure is:
`ble.scan(services, seconds, success, failure);`

And in the angular wrapper for this plugin you can see the scan function is implemented as:

``` javascript
scan: function (services, seconds) {
        var q = $q.defer();
        ble.scan(services, seconds, function (result) {
          q.resolve(result);
        }, function (error) {
          q.reject(error);
        });
        return q.promise;
      }
```

The principle behind this is called Promises. I'm not an expert on this either, but there are tutorials online that you can read up on. But just by observation, you can see how the success and failure portions become "resolve" and "reject" and you return the "promise". 

You can make these implementations for any/all of the functions you want available from the plugin. And that's kind of the basics of the whole process I think. 
. Well what is the issue you're running into exactly? Did you make sure to add the plugin to the ionic project with "cordova plugin add ..."? The angular wrappers/ng-cordova still need you to add the plugin separately.
. You got it working? That's great! Honestly though, for such a simple plugin that only has one function, I don't really see the need for constructing an angular wrapper for it. It takes only a couple lines to get the data you need. But in any case, in your code for the wrapper, the code inside the `function()` block after the `defer()` call should basically be the same code as you would have if you were calling the plugin directly without the wrapper. So according to the plugin readme, it would look something like this:

``` javascript
var deviceInfo = cordova.require("cordova/plugin/DeviceInformation");
deviceInfo.get(function(result) {
        console.log("result = " + result);
    }, function() {
        console.log("error");
    });
```

But except of console logs, you would put the `resolve` and `reject` functions.
