evgd:
Hi @gortok,
Thank you for your integration with new push plugin! 
I tested it and I was a bit confused with implementation...
Here is my PR.
I wanted to keep it simple and merged "initialize" and "register" method because in common case you will call them sequentially.
Possible use case of "initialize" without "register" - unregistration but it's not the case with current push plugin - https://github.com/phonegap/phonegap-plugin-push/issues/208.
Otherwise there is chance to miss "registrationId" as "PushNotification.init" registers on initialization:

``` javascript
   setTimeout(function() {
       exec(success, fail, 'PushNotification', 'init', [options]);
   }, 10);
```

Register resolves with RegistrationId(token), rejects with registration error, subscribes to "notificationReceived" and "error" (as per current state of Push Plugin code errors triggers only during registration).

"onNotification" and "onError" methods - no need to call them, we can subscribe on "registration" to not miss "$cordovaPushV5:notificationReceived" and "$cordovaPushV5:errorOccurred".

``` javascript
onNotification : function () {
// It's just subscription and can be done on register call.
    $timeout(function () {
      push.on('notification', function (notification) {
        $rootScope.$emit('$cordovaPushV5:notificationReceived', notification);
  });
});
```

Example for this PR:

``` javascript
$rootScope.$on('$cordovaPushV5:notificationReceived', function (event, notification) {
    // ...
});

$rootScope.$on('$cordovaPushV5:errorOccurred', function (event, error) {
    // ...
});

$cordovaPushV5.register(options).then(function (token) {
    // ...
}, function (error) {
    // ...
});
```
. @philmerrell 
Thank you for feedback. I agree with you that there is inconsistent with phonegap-plugin-push API. I thought that it would be handy to have "init" and "registration" in single method. We should consider that phonegap-plugin-push API consists of "init" method and "registration", "notification" and "error" events which means to keep it fully consistent there should be only "init" and "$cordovaPushV5:registrationId" event. I think some deviations is acceptable if they are well documented. As from my experience, I started using push plugin right from ngCordova examples and then, just to know how it works, checked push plugin documentation.
For me either one or two methods will look fine. But there is also other changes from PR aimed to prevent missing events(1), missed digest(2) and just to not force write sequence "$cordovaPushV5.onNotification(); $rootScope.$on('$cordovaPushV5:notificationReceived', ...);" that can be made implicitly (3).
Below original implementation with comments on points.

``` javascript
// (3) it just subscribes to "push" events. If you don't want them just don't listen '$cordovaPushV5:notificationReceived' rootScope event.
onNotification : function () { 
// (2) no need of timeout here because it doesn't touch scope.
    $timeout(function () { 
      push.on('notification', function (notification) {
// (2) but here we will want to wrap "$emit" with $timeout, $evalAsync or $apply to execute in "angular" context and force digest cycle.
        $rootScope.$emit('$cordovaPushV5:notificationReceived', notification);
      });
    });
}
```

With (1) it's not likely to happen if you know that "init" and "register" must be called sequentially (no postpone of "register" execution). Somebody can think that it's OK to init service at startup and register after some user interactions (like login, or press button, etc).
Another case for ideal latency world but it might happen if your have tons of watches for example:

``` javascript
// this initializes "Registration" process. Check android code here https://github.com/phonegap/phonegap-plugin-push/blob/master/www/push.js#L60-L62 you have only 10ms to subsribe to events...
$cordovaPushV5.initialize() 
    .then(() => {
// I'm not aware of this behaviour and wanted to subscribe "notification" and "error" first, then make "register"
        $cordovaPushV5.onError(); // digest loop
        $cordovaPushV5.onNotification(); // digest loop
        $cordovaPushV5.register((registrationId) => ...); // are we still in 10ms range here?
    });
```
. @ronyrun complete example for this branch

